The Heroes Book Tour - Elizabeth, NJ
Book Signing/Art Exhibition Event featuring the release of the highly anticipated book, Heroes of the Haitian Revolution.

By
Frantz Derenoncourt, Jr.

Join us as we celebrate the release of the new book Heroes of the Haitian Revolution by publisher Thorobred Books featuring author Frantz Derenoncourt, Jr. and illustrator Kervin Andre.

There will also be a display of The Haitian Heroes and Sheroes Art Exhibition which features original paintings of our revered ancestors by talented artist Kervin Andre.

Hear stories and see images of well known Heroes like Toussaint Louverture, Jean-Jacques Dessalines, and Henry Christophe as well as some not so well known Heroes like Jeannot Bullet, Jean-Francois Papillon, and Moyse.

This will be the 2nd collaboration project by Frantz and Kervin who brought you Sheroes of the Haitian Revolution in 2019.

Pick up your signed copies and make sure you hang around for The Haitian Heroes Live Podcast as the author and artist will conduct a live interview during the event.

Limited Space

Free RSVP

Date and time

Fri, January 6, 2023, 6:00 PM – 9:00 PM EST

Location

Elizabeth City Chamber of Commerce 142 Broad St. Elizabeth, NJ 07208

The minutemen 
June 8, 1780, when a column of 5,000 British Regulars landed in Port Elizabeth. The British marched down Elizabeth Avenue heading west, where they would attack the Continental Army.
Just fifteen Elizabeth Minutemen positioned around Union Square, held them off and even wounded their General, Lord Stirling. The Minutemen continued to attack them as they continued toward Springfield, delaying them enough for Washington’s Army to survive, and then drive them out of New Jersey. #elizabethnj #akomicsart #newarkairportterminala #kervinandrecollection #blackhistory

femmecuratorarts Femme Curator Arts, presents "The Art of Culture " a radical response of creative expression through visual and performing arts. The all-female curatorial team celebrates its 8th annual art exhibition during the Newark Arts Festival, showcasing multigenerational visual artists, live performances, and communal art activations.
Curators Kween Moore, Jadeley Louis-Jean, and Jennica Washington explore themes of thriving culture, rooted in traditions and making a way in this world, and what it means to create a space for "work to live on".
Hip hop has served as a major source of inspiration and influence for the last 50 years, creating dynamic music and art that is unique and timeless. This exhibition is savory, rich in its simplicity, and thought provoking at every turn.
Run of Events 9/28-10/1

Thank you to my city 

I wanted to create a piece highlighting the contribution of Blacks in the American Revolution.  New Jersey played a pivotal role in the American Revolution, and the city of Elizabeth and its special force of Minutemen were monumental in major battles.  As a student in the Elizabeth school system, I learned about the Minutemen and their contributions, yet I was never able to identify with any of them.  I couldn’t envision any of them looking like me, a black man.  My piece at the airport is my attempt to not only honor those brave black men who fought in the American Revolution while they were being treated as sub-humans, but also to create a piece that was identifiable to those who look like me.
